   1  # Agent
   2  
   3  A local, tool-driven coding assistant that talks to an OpenAI-compatible LLM endpoint (e.g. `llama-server` from `llama.cpp`) and runs an autonomous file/shell tool loop. It is built to survive long sessions: it checkpoints every turn, summarizes older history in the background, recovers from malformed tool calls, and catches common hallucinations before they poison context.
   4  
   5  ## Quick start
   6  
   7  1. Start an OpenAI-compatible LLM server locally. The default endpoint is `http://127.0.0.1:8080`:
   8  
   9     ```bash
  10     llama-server -m your-model.gguf --port 8080
  11     ```
  12  
  13  2. (Optional) create a `config.json` in your working directory to override defaults — see [Configuration](#configuration).
  14  
  15  3. Run the agent:
  16  
  17     ```bash
  18     python agent.py "fix the failing test in tests/test_parser.py"
  19     ```
  20  
  21  ## CLI
  22  
  23  ```
  24  python agent.py [OPTIONS] [PROMPT...]
  25  ```
  26  
  27  | Flag | Description |
  28  | --- | --- |
  29  | `-a`, `--auto` | Automation mode — run the prompt and exit; no interactive loop. |
  30  | `-c`, `--continue` | Resume from the last checkpoint and drop into an interactive session. Combine with `-a` for auto-resume-and-exit. |
  31  | `-r N`, `--repeat N` | Run the prompt `N` times with fresh state each run. `0` or omitted means run indefinitely. Implies `-a`. |
  32  | `--nudge` | When the model returns a text-only response (no tool calls), auto-nudge it to keep going instead of stopping. Off by default. |
  33  | `--no-tui` | Disable the `prompt_toolkit` TUI and use a plain `input()` prompt. The TUI is on by default in any interactive mode and falls back to plain input automatically if `prompt_toolkit` isn't installed. |
  34  | `--verbose` | Start the session with full (uncompacted) tool output. Toggle in-session with `/verbose`. |
  35  | `PROMPT...` | Initial prompt. Optional; in interactive mode you'll be prompted if omitted. |
  36  
  37  Press **Escape twice** within 400ms to cancel a streaming response. In the TUI this works while the model is streaming; the prompt itself uses `prompt_toolkit`'s native key handling.
  38  
  39  ### Interactive TUI (default)
  40  
  41  When running interactively, the agent uses a `prompt_toolkit` front-end with:
  42  
  43  - A **bottom toolbar** showing `cwd · model · message count · context ~% · verbose state`.
  44  - **Completion** for slash commands (`/he<Tab>`) and `@path` file refs (`@src/<Tab>`).
  45  - **Input history** navigable with ↑ / ↓.
  46  - **Key bindings**: `Enter` submits, `Ctrl+N` inserts a literal newline.
  47  
  48  Pass `--no-tui` to use the plain `input()` prompt instead. The `prompt_toolkit` package is an optional dependency — if it isn't installed, the agent prints a one-line notice and falls back to the plain prompt automatically.
  49  
  50  ### Interactive commands
  51  
  52  In the interactive loop, lines starting with `/` are commands:
  53  
  54  | Command | Description |
  55  | --- | --- |
  56  | `/help` | List available commands. |
  57  | `/clear` | Clear conversation history and start a fresh session log. |
  58  | `/context` | Show current context usage as an Aurora-gradient bar with token counts. |
  59  | `/model` | Pick a different model from the server's `/v1/models` endpoint (summarizer keeps its original). |
  60  | `/verbose` | Toggle compact vs. full tool-result output. Full results are always logged regardless. |
  61  | `/tools [N\|all]` | Show buffered tool calls with a one-line result preview. Default `/tools` shows every call in the rolling buffer (50 most recent); `/tools N` shows the last `N`; `/tools all` is an explicit synonym for the default. |
  62  | `exit` / `quit` | End the session. |
  63  
  64  ### Colors
  65  
  66  The terminal UI uses the **Aurora** palette (violet → sky → mint) via `theme.py`. `NO_COLOR=1` or piping to a file disables all colors and cursor escapes automatically.
  67  
  68  ## How it works
  69  
  70  Each cycle is a turn loop:
  71  
  72  1. Build a context window from recent history plus an async summary of older history.
  73  2. Stream a response from the LLM.
  74  3. Execute any tool calls.
  75  4. Feed results back in and repeat until the model stops calling tools, a cycle limit is hit, or the user cancels.
  76  
  77  The loop has a few guardrails worth knowing about:
  78  
  79  - **Checkpointing.** Conversation history and summary state are written to `.agent/state/conversation_checkpoint.json` every turn. `--continue` resumes from there.
  80  - **Async summarization.** If a summary endpoint is configured, a background thread condenses older messages while the main model keeps working. The summary is swapped in when ready.
  81  - **Cycle limits & wind-down.** After `cycle.max_turns` turns (default 100), the agent is asked to wrap up; after `cycle.wind_down_turns` more turns it is forced to stop.
  82  - **Text-loop detection.** If the model emits the same text three times in a row, the cycle ends instead of looping forever.
  83  - **Hallucination guards.** When the model claims to have read a file it never actually read, the fabricated message is stripped and a correction injected. Malformed tool-call JSON is also salvaged heuristically.
  84  - **Tool recovery.** When a tool fails with a recognizable error (e.g. bad line numbers), `tool_recovery.py` tries to re-run it with corrected parameters via a lightweight LLM call.
  85  - **Context overflow handling.** Three consecutive HTTP 500s from the LLM endpoint are treated as context overflow — the agent trims history and retries.
  86  
  87  ## Project layout
  88  
  89  ```
  90  agent.py            # Main loop, streaming, context management, checkpointing
  91  callbacks.py        # UI callback interface — NullCallbacks, TerminalCallbacks, safe_cb
  92  commands.py         # Slash-command dispatcher (/help, /clear, /verbose, /tools, …)
  93  tui.py              # prompt_toolkit front-end (default in interactive mode; --no-tui to disable)
  94  cancel.py           # Double-escape cancel handler
  95  spinner.py          # Aurora-pulsed waiting/streaming/done visual feedback
  96  theme.py            # Aurora color palette + single source of ANSI escapes
  97  token_utils.py      # Tokenizer (Gemma) with char-based fallback
  98  tool_recovery.py    # Auto-recovery from recoverable tool errors
  99  tools/              # Built-in tools (see below)
 100    file.py           # read / write / insert / append / delete / list
 101    exec_command.py   # Shell execution with background-session support
 102    search_files.py   # Grep-like search with glob and case controls
 103    read_pdf.py       # PDF text extraction (PyMuPDF)
 104    web_fetch.py      # URL → markdown, saved to disk with inline preview
 105    think.py          # Deep-reasoning tool via a separate thinking call
 106    task_tracker.py   # Persistent task list in .agent/state/tasks.json
 107    sleep.py          # Pause execution
 108  .agent/             # Runtime artifacts (created on first run, gitignored)
 109    state/
 110      conversation_checkpoint.json
 111      tasks.json
 112      current-state.json
 113      cycle.txt
 114      fetched/        # Cached web_fetch output
 115    history/
 116      session-*.log   # Per-session verbose logs
 117  ```
 118  
 119  Agent-specific tools can also live in `./tools/` alongside your working directory — they are auto-discovered and registered on startup.
 120  
 121  ## Configuration
 122  
 123  Drop a `config.json` in the working directory to override any of the built-in defaults. The top-level sections are:
 124  
 125  - **`backends`** — registry with `main` and `summary` entries; each carries a `kind` (currently `"llamacpp"`; a `"bedrock"` kind is planned, see `plan/bedrock-integration.md`) plus kind-specific keys (`base_url`, `model`, …). Preferred shape going forward.
 126  - **`llm`**, **`summary`** — legacy flat blocks (`base_url`, `model`, …). Still supported for back-compat: at load time they are synthesized into `backends.main` / `backends.summary` with `kind: "llamacpp"`. New configs should use `backends`; old configs need no change.
 127  - **`generation`** — `temperature`, `top_p`, `top_k`, `presence_penalty`.
 128  - **`context`** — `ctx_size`, `max_tokens`, `max_full_lines`, `preview_lines`, `summary_threshold`, `summary_max_chars`, `max_context_messages`. Controls how history is sized and when it gets summarized.
 129  - **`cycle`** — `max_turns`, `wind_down_turns`, `max_text_only`. Per-cycle turn budget and text-only nudge cap.
 130  - **`retry`** — `max_retries`, `base_delay_seconds`, `max_delay_seconds`, `backoff_multiplier`, `jitter_factor`. Exponential backoff for transient LLM errors.
 131  
 132  Example using the registry shape:
 133  
 134  ```json
 135  {
 136    "backends": {
 137      "main":    { "kind": "llamacpp", "base_url": "http://127.0.0.1:8080", "model": "gemma-4-31B" },
 138      "summary": { "kind": "llamacpp", "base_url": "http://127.0.0.1:8082", "model": "gemma-4-E4B", "enabled": true, "max_wait_on_save": 10 }
 139    },
 140    "context": { "ctx_size": 32768 },
 141    "cycle":   { "max_turns": 50 }
 142  }
 143  ```
 144  
 145  Equivalent legacy shape (still works, synthesized into the registry at load time):
 146  
 147  ```json
 148  {
 149    "llm":     { "base_url": "http://127.0.0.1:8080", "model": "gemma-4-31B" },
 150    "summary": { "base_url": "http://127.0.0.1:8082", "model": "gemma-4-E4B", "enabled": true, "max_wait_on_save": 10 },
 151    "context": { "ctx_size": 32768 },
 152    "cycle":   { "max_turns": 50 }
 153  }
 154  ```
 155  
 156  ## Dependencies
 157  
 158  - Python 3.7+
 159  - `requests` — HTTP to the LLM endpoint
 160  - `transformers` + `torch` — Gemma tokenizer (optional; falls back to a character-based estimate if missing)
 161  - `PyMuPDF` (`fitz`) — PDF extraction, used by `tools/read_pdf.py`
 162  - `markdownify` — HTML → Markdown conversion, used by `tools/web_fetch.py`
 163  - `prompt_toolkit` — powers the default interactive TUI (bottom toolbar, completion, input history). Technically **optional** — if it isn't installed, interactive mode automatically falls back to a plain `input()` prompt and prints a one-line notice. Pass `--no-tui` to force the plain prompt even when `prompt_toolkit` is available. Install with `pip install prompt_toolkit`.
 164  - A running OpenAI-compatible LLM server (e.g. `llama-server`)
 165  - Bash, and a TTY for the cancel handler
 166  
 167  ## State and logs
 168  
 169  Everything runtime lives under `.agent/` in the working directory:
 170  
 171  - `.agent/state/conversation_checkpoint.json` — last checkpoint for `--continue`
 172  - `.agent/state/tasks.json` — persistent task list used by the `task_tracker` tool
 173  - `.agent/state/current-state.json` — per-cycle scratch state
 174  - `.agent/state/cycle.txt` — monotonic cycle counter
 175  - `.agent/state/fetched/` — cached `web_fetch` downloads
 176  - `.agent/history/session-*.log` — verbose per-session logs
 177  
 178  Delete the `.agent/` directory to start completely fresh. The whole tree is gitignored.

